<P><STRONG>GluCylinders</STRONG> is sample C++ code illustrating how to =
draw=20
cylinders and slant cylinders with the gluQuadric routines of OpenGL. =
&nbsp; It=20
is intended to accompany the book <EM><STRONG>3D Computer Graphics: A=20
mathematical approach with OpenGL</STRONG>, </EM>by S. Buss, Cambridge=20
University Press, 2003. &nbsp; However, it can be used independently as=20
well.</P>
<P><STRONG>GluCylinders</STRONG> Draws a cylinder and slant cylinder. =
The red=20
cylinder is drawn without any face culling and without any top or bottom =
disks.=20
The green cylinder is drawn with back faces culled, and with a top and =
bottom=20
disk. </P>
<P>Arrow keys control the viewpoint. The command "w" toggles wireframe =
mode, but=20
since there is no Phong lighting the cylinders look terrible in "Fill" =
mode.=20
</P>
<P>To use these in your own code, just copy out the set of four routines =
at the=20
end of <STRONG>GluCylinders.c</STRONG>. The code as written generates =
cylinders=20
that have smooth normals. If you need texture coordinates generated, you =
will=20
need to call <STRONG>gluQuadricTexture</STRONG>, for this, see the =
OpenGL=20
documentation (in the red book, or elsewhere). </P>
